探索式資料分析 統計圖表¶

(參考資料: 吳漢銘教授講義)¶

The Doubs dataset have been collected at 30 sites along the Doubs River (near the France-Switzerland border in the Jura Mountains.)¶

  • DoubsAbu.csv: contains coded abundances of 27 fish species.
  • DoubsEnv.csv: contains 11 environmental variables related to the hydrology, geomorphology and chemistry of the river.
  • DoubsSpa.csv: contains the geographical coordinates (Cartesian, X and Y) of the sites.

Overall Distribution of Abundances¶

In [8]:
abundance_class = []
for col in df_Abu:
    abundance_class.append(df_Abu[col].value_counts())
abundance_class = pd.DataFrame(abundance_class)

abundance_class.sum(axis=0).plot(kind='bar')

plt.xlabel('Abundance class')
plt.ylabel('Frequency')
plt.xticks(rotation=0)
plt.title('Overall Distribution of Abundances')
plt.tight_layout()

fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 4, figsize=(15, 4))
cols = ['TRU', 'OMB', 'BAR', 'BCO']
titles = ['Brown trout', 'Grayling', 'Barbel', 'Common bream']

for (ax, col, title) in zip(axes.ravel(), cols, titles):
    ax.plot(df_Spa['x'], df_Spa['y'])
    for i in range(df_Abu.shape[0]):
        ax.scatter(df_Spa['x'][i], df_Spa['y'][i], marker='o', s=np.square(df_Abu.iloc[i][col])*30, facecolor='w', edgecolor='k')
    ax.set_xlabel('x coordinate (km)')
    ax.set_ylabel('y coordinate (km)')
    ax.set_title(title)
plt.tight_layout()

Compare Species: Number of Occurrences¶

At how many sites does each species occur? Calculate the relative frequencies of species (proportion of the number of sites) and plot histograms.

In [11]:
fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(12, 4))
axes = axes.ravel()

species_occurance = (df_Abu > 0).astype(int).sum(axis=0).sort_values()
species_occurance.plot(kind='hist', bins=np.linspace(0, 30, 7), edgecolor='w', ax=axes[0])
axes[0].set_xlabel('Number of Occurance')
axes[0].set_ylabel('Number of Species')
axes[0].set_title('Species Occurance')

species_occurance = species_occurance / 30 * 100
species_occurance.plot(kind='hist', bins=np.linspace(0, 100, 11), edgecolor='w', ax=axes[1])
axes[1].set_xlabel('Frequency of Occurance (%)')
axes[1].set_ylabel('Number of Species')
axes[1].set_title('Species Relatice Frequencies')
plt.tight_layout()

Compare Sites: Species Richness¶

Now that we have seen at how many sites each species is present, we may want to know how many species are present at each site (species richness).

In [12]:
fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(12, 4))
axes = axes.ravel()
species_richness = (df_Abu > 0).astype(int).sum(axis=1)
axes[0].plot(np.arange(1, df_Abu.shape[0]+1), species_richness)
for i in range(df_Spa.shape[0]):
    axes[0].annotate(str(i+1), (i+1, species_richness[i]))
axes[0].set_xlabel('Position of sites along the river')
axes[0].set_ylabel('Species richness')
axes[0].set_title('Species richness vs.\nUpstream-Downstream Gradient')
axes[1].plot(df_Spa['x'], df_Spa['y'], c='b')
for i in range(df_Spa.shape[0]):
    axes[1].scatter(df_Spa['x'][i], df_Spa['y'][i], marker='o', s=np.square(species_richness[i]), c='indianred', edgecolor='b')
axes[1].set_xlabel('x coordinate (km)')
axes[1].set_ylabel('y coordinate (km)')
axes[1].set_title('Map of species richness')

Bubble Maps of Some Environmental Variables¶

  • Which ones of these maps display an upstream-downstream gradient?
  • How could you explain the spatial patterns of the other variables?
In [14]:
fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 4, figsize=(15, 4))
axes = axes.ravel()
cols = ['alt', 'deb', 'oxy', 'nit']
colors = ['red', 'green', 'blue', 'brown']
titles = ['Altitude', 'Discharge', 'Oxygen', 'Nitrate']

marker_size = df_Env.copy()
for col in df_Env:
    Vmin = df_Env[col].min()
    Vmax = df_Env[col].max()
    marker_size[col] = (df_Env[col] - Vmin) / (Vmax - Vmin)
    
for (col, title, color, ax) in zip(cols, titles, colors, axes):
    ax.plot(df_Spa['x'], df_Spa['y'], c='b')
    for i in range(df_Spa.shape[0]):
        ax.scatter(df_Spa['x'][i], df_Spa['y'][i], marker='o', s=marker_size[col][i] * 400, c=color, edgecolor='k')
        ax.set_xlabel('x coordinate (km)')
        ax.set_ylabel('y coordinate (km)')
        ax.set_title(title)

plt.tight_layout()
plt.savefig('env.png')

Simple Transformation of An Environmental Variable¶

  • Simple transformations, such as the log transformation, can be used to improve the distributions of some variables (make it closer to the normal distribution).
  • Because environmental variables are dimensionally heterogeneous (expressed in different units and scales), many statistical analyses require their standardization to zero mean and unit variance. These centred and scaled variables are called z-scores.
